Journal of Cardiovascular Computed Tomography. 2019 Mar 29;0(0). Available from: http://www.journalofcardiovascularct.com/article/S1934-5925(18)30618-X/abstract.

Patient position
A channel monitoring the patients position.

Patient rotation longitudinal
A channel monitoring the patients rotation around the bodys longitudinal (head  feet) axis.

Patient elevation
A channel monitoring the angle of elevation of the patient against horizontal.

Hyperventilation begin
Begin of deepened or accelerated breathing.

Hyperventilation end
End of deepened or accelerated breathing.

Post-hyperventilation
Point in time after end of hyperventilation.

Airflow Thermistor
Airflow measured by a thermistor sensor.

Airflow Thermocouple
Airflow measured by a thermocouple sensor.

Airflow Nasal Prong
Airflow measurement by a nasal prong.

Airflow PVDF
Airflow measurement by a nasal piezoelectric polyvinylidenefluoride sensor.

Airflow CPAP
Airflow measurement by a Continuous Positive Airway Pressure device.

Airflow
Airflow measured by an unspecified method or device.

PAP Pressure
Pressure delivered by a positive airway pressure device like a CPAP or BiPAP machine.

PAP Leak Pressure
Pressure of air leaking from a positive airway pressure device like a CPAP or BiPAP machine.

PAP Tidal Volume
Tidal volume during breathing when subject is using a positive airway pressure device like a CPAP or BiPAP machine.

Esophageal Pressure
Pressure in the esophagus measured by esophageal manometry.

Respiratory Pressure
Respiratory pressure measured with an unspecified method or device.

Thoracic Respiratory Inductance
Respiratory effort delivered by a respiratory inductance plethysmography (RIP) belt applied on the patients thorax.

Abdominal Respiratory Inductance
Respiratory effort delivered by a respiratory inductance plethysmography (RIP) belt applied on the patients abdomen.

Thoracic Respiratory PVDF
Respiratory effort delivered by a piezoelectric polyvinylidenefluoride sensor belt applied on the patients thorax.

Abdominal Respiratory PVDF
Respiratory effort delivered by a piezoelectric polyvinylidenefluoride sensor belt applied on the patients abdomen.

Thoracic Respiratory Effort
Respiratory effort measured by an unspecified method or device on the patients thorax.

Abdominal Respiratory Effort
Respiratory effort measured by an unspecified method or device on the patients abdomen.

Respiratory Effort
Respiratory effort measured by an unspecified method or device.

CO2 Transcutaneous
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the respiratory gases measured transcutaneously.

CO2 Waveform End-tidal Main-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the end-tidal main-stream respiratory gases.

CO2 Trend End-tidal Main-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the end-tidal main-stream respiratory gases averaged over time.

CO2 Waveform End-tidal Side-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the end-tidal side-stream respiratory gases.

CO2 Trend End-tidal Side-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the end-tidal side-stream respiratory gases averaged over time.

CO2 Waveform Main-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the main-stream respiratory gases.

CO2 Waveform Side-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the side-stream respiratory gases.

CO2 Trend Main-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the main-stream respiratory gases averaged over time.

CO2 Trend Side-stream
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide measured in the side-stream respiratory gases averaged over time.

CO2 Respiration
Partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the respiratory gases measured using an unspecified method or device.

concept.display: RT Treatment with Ad Hoc Planning
concept.definition:
RT Treatment with Ad Hoc Planning
Radiotherapy treatment delivery where treatment parameters are defined at the treatment device, rather than specified by a treatment plan.

concept.display: Imaging Agent Administration Step Sequence Number
concept.definition:
Imaging Agent Administration Step Sequence Number
The order in which Imaging Agent administration steps are planned to be performed.

Operator decision to terminate treatment
Decision was made by the operator of the equipment to discontinue treatment.

Patient decision to terminate treatment
Decision was made by the patient to discontinue treatment.

Physician decision to terminate treatment
Decision was made by the physician to discontinue treatment.

Treatment Terminated
Treatment delivery of this RT Radiation was terminated.

Resolved by overriding Interlock
An out-of-tolerance delivery parameter was accepted or re-specified and treatment delivery was continued.

Resolved by repositioning Patient
The patient was re-positioned and treatment delivery was continued.

Bolus Present
A bolus is confirmed to be present.

Cone Present
A cone is confirmed to be present.

Block Present
A block is confirmed to be present.

Applicator Present
An applicator is confirmed to be present.

Headframe Present
A headframe is confirmed to be present.

Inappropriate Patient Orientation
The patient could not be positioned on the patient positioning device in a way, that the shape of treatment area has an unacceptable orientation to match the intended target area.

Inappropriate Patient Position
The patient could not be positioned on the patient positioning device in a way, that the that the shape of treatment area radiated the intended target area.

Machine Not Available
The machine intended to be used for treatment was not available.

Change in Patient Anatomy
The patients anatomy is found to be inconsistent with the patient model used during planning to the extent that treatment delivery was impacted.

Machine Calibration Adjustment
A re-calibration of the treatment device impacted the treatment delivery.

Unavailability of a Beam Modifier
A planned Beam Modifier was not available at the time of treatment.

Machine Capability License Expired
A capability of the treatment device was not available because the corresponding license expired.

Beam Targeting Tolerance Violation
Beam targeting parameters have been adjusted in a way that violated a clinical tolerance.

Meterset Tolerance Violation
A Meterset value has been adjusted in a way that violated a clinical tolerance.

Delivery Rate Tolerance Violation
A Delivery Rate has been adjusted in a way that violated a clinical tolerance.

Jaw Position Tolerance Violation
Jaw positions exceeded the machine tolerance.

MLC Position Tolerance Violation
One or more MLC leave positions exceeded the machine tolerance.

Source Position Tolerance Violation
The Source Position angle exceeded the machine tolerance.

Dose Rate Tolerance Violation
The dose rate exceeded the machine tolerance.

Primary Fluence Monitoring System Interlock
An interlock triggered by the primary fluence-monitoring system.

Secondary Fluence Monitoring System Interlock
An interlock triggered by the secondary fluence-monitoring system (also known as Secondary Dose Monitoring System [IEC 60601-2-1]).

Timer Interlock
An interlock triggered by a controlling timer.

Door Interlock
An interlock triggered by a door being open.

Patient Motion Interlock
An interlock triggered by patient movement.

concept.display: Family history of non-melanoma skin cancer
concept.definition:
Family history of non-melanoma skin cancer
Information about non-melanoma skin cancers in blood relatives of the patient.

concept.display: Family history of melanoma in situ
concept.definition:
Family history of melanoma in situ
Information about in situ melanoma in blood relatives of the patient.

History of non-melanoma skin cancer
Information about non-melanoma skin cancers in the patient.

Number of malignant melanomas
The number of malignant melanomas the patient has had diagnosed.

Number of melanomas in situ
The number of in situ melanomas the patient has had diagnosed.

Firm skin lesion
A skin lesion that is firm on palpation.

Raised skin lesion
A lesion that is raised from the skin surface on palpation.

concept.display: Number of first-degree relatives affected by malignant melanoma
concept.definition:
Number of first-degree relatives affected by malignant melanoma
The number of direct relatives (i.e., parent, sibling, offspring) who have malignant melanoma.

Region in Space
A continuous part of space, not necessarily associated with a particular image.

Referenced Region of Interest Identifier
A reference to an identifier of a Region of Interest.
For example, the value of ROI Number (3006,0022) within an Item of Structure Set ROI Sequence (3006,0020) in an Instance of RT Structure Set Storage SOP Class.

Centerline
A path along the long axis of an elongated finding or feature, which is equidistant from its surface, such as along the center of the lumen of a vessel.

Stimulation Mode
Mode of stimulation used when applying stimulation techniques during procedure.

Stimulus Sample Position
The sample number where the first stimulation event takes place.
Sample position in waveform recordings starts at 1.

Stimulus Time Offset
The time offset where the stimulation starts, relative to the start time of the recorded waveform data.

Number of Stimulus Events
How many stimulation events took place.

Frequency of Stimulus Events
The frequency with which periodic stimulation occurs.

Accumulated Dose Data
Description of dosimetric-related values that can be summarized for the entire scope of accumulation.

Irradiation Event Summary Data
Description of dosimetric-related values that can be summarized for a single irradiation event.

Reference Point Dosimetry
Description of the reference point definition and accumulated dose values at the reference point.

Is Rejected Acquisition
This acquisition of data (e.g., for constructing an image) was for some reason unsatisfactory.

Reason for Rejecting Acquisition
The reason that data (e.g., for constructing an image) was rejected.

Irradiation Details
Description of the radiation dose characteristics independent of an irradiation event.

RDSR Frame of Reference Origin
The component that is used to define the origin of the RDSR RCS.

RDSR Frame of Reference Description
The description of the RDSR reference coordinate system. It should include a description of where the origin is, as well as the orientation of the coordinate system.

Radiation Source Characteristics
Description of the radiation source characteristics

X-Ray Filter Thickness
The thickness of the X-Ray filter

Reported Value Type
Describes if a reported value is a mean, median, maximum, minimum, etc.

Radiation Technique
Description of radiation technique details

Filtration
Description of a filter

Attenuators
Description of attenuators

Radiation Output
Description of the output measurement point dose accumulation timing and values.

concept.display: Air Kerma at Output Measurement Point
concept.definition:
Air Kerma at Output Measurement Point
The air kerma (in mGy) accumulated at the output measurement point during a given period of time.

Radiation Field Area
Description of the radiation field area and corresponding timing and source index.

Radiation Field Outline
A list of three-dimensional coordinates that describe the perimeter of the radiation field. The points shall be coplanar and are limited to describing either polygons or ellipses.

Value Timing
Specifies when a value was determined within a period of time.

X-Ray Source Reference Coordinate System
Description of the X-Ray source coordinate reference system and the transformation matrix that relates it to the RDSR reference coordinate system

Transformation Matrix
A transformation matrix that relates one coordinate system to another

Center of Rotation
The point about which an object rotates

Rotation Plane Normal Point
A point defining a vector relative to the center of rotation that defines a normal vector of the rotation plane

Rotation Angle
The angle about the center of rotation for a rotating object

Beam Position
Description of component positions described in the X-Ray source reference coordinate system

Output Measurement Point Position
The three-dimensional coordinate of the output measurement position. The output measurement position is described in the X-Ray source reference coordinate system.

Reference Point Position
The three-dimensional coordinate of the reference point position. The reference point position is described in the X-Ray source reference coordinate system. The reference point may be at the same position as the output measurement point.

Identification of the Attenuator
Textual identification for each attenuator described. The identifier is used to link the description of the attenuator to its position described in the beam position or attenuator position template. The identifier shall not change during the scope of accumulation described in 10040, and shall not be repeated.

Attenuator Position
Description of positions and corresponding timing for attenuators

Patient Attenuation Characteristics
Description of various patient attenuation characteristics that may be known by the system and may change during the course of the scope of accumulation

Procedure Characteristics
Description of various procedure characteristics that may change during a study and may be useful to aid in dosimetry or quality assurance

Attenuator Characteristics
Characteristics of an X-Ray attenuator used as either a filter or attenuating object in the X-Ray beam. Includes a description of actual or equivalent material, as well as thickness information.

Duration of Time Period
All the points in time throughout a defined period of time

Beginning of Time Period
The point in time at the beginning of a defined period of time

End of Time Period
The point in time at the end of a defined period of time

Middle of Time Period
The point in time at the middle of a defined period of time

Room Origin
The origin of the Frame of Reference is defined as part of the room in which the equipment is located

Equipment Origin
The origin of the Frame of Reference is defined as part of the equipment

Patient Support Origin
The origin of the Frame of Reference is defined as part of the patient support

Isocenter Origin
The origin of the Frame of Reference is defined as the isocenter of the imaging system

Patient Coordinate System Origin
The origin of the RDSR Frame of Reference is defined as the origin of the patient coordinate system in the images.

10 cm Dosimetry Phantom
A dosimetry phantom consisting of a 100 mm diameter polymethyl methacrylate (PMMA) cylinder. The phantom will be at least 140 mm in length. The phantom will be longer than the length of the sensitive volume of the radiation detector used for measurements. The phantom will have five holes just large enough to accept a radiation detector and will be parallel to the axis of symmetry: one hole at the center, and four holes with their centers 10 mm below the surface of the phantom at 90 intervals. For the holes not used during a measurement, properly fitting insert parts made of PMMA will be used.

Magnetic field strength
Nominal field strength of MR magnet.

Endorectal coil used
Indication of whether endorectal coil was used during MR examination.

Endorectal coil type
Type of the endorectal coil used during MR examination.

Inflatable endorectal coil fill substance
Substance used to fill endorectal coil in order to suppress distortion artifacts during MR examination.

Cross-sectional scan plane orientation
Orientation of the plane defining image acquisition.

Dynamic contrast-enhanced temporal resolution
Time between acquisition of imaging samples corresponding to the same tissue location during dynamic contrast-enhanced examination.

Genitourinary History
Clinical history of the patient related to the genitourinary health.

Imaging Study Quality
Assessment of the imaging study related to its quality, as defined by the compliance with the technical acquisition requirements or as perceived by the reader.

Imaging Series Quality
Assessment of a specific imaging series related to its quality, as defined by the compliance with the technical acquisition requirements or as perceived by the reader.

Reporting system
Standard or guideline used to perform structured evaluation of imaging study.

Prostate MRI relevant procedure information
Information relevant for evaluation of prostate MR imaging study.

Prostate Imaging Findings
Findings identified in prostate images

Overall Prostate Finding
Finding relating to the overall assessment of the prostate gland

Localized Prostate Finding
Finding relating to the localized entities within the prostate gland

Prostate relational measurements
Measurements relating localized findings to the prostate gland

Distance from neurovascular bundle
Distance between a finding and a neurovascular bundle

Lesion capsular contact length
Length of the portion of the lesion abutting the prostate capsule as observed in the image.

Extra-prostatic Finding
Finding identified in prostate MRI that is located outside of the prostate gland.

PI-RADS Localized Abnormality Assessment
Evaluation of a localized abnormality within the gland using Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) guidelines.

PI-RADS T2WI Lesion Assessment
Assessment of the lesions characteristics based on its appearance in T2-weighted MR images following the Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) guidelines.

PI-RADS DWI Lesion Assessment
Assessment of the lesions characteristics based on its appearance in diffusion-weighted MR images following the Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) guidelines.

PI-RADS DCE Lesion Assessment
Assessment of the lesions characteristics based on its appearance in Dynamic Contrast-enhanced MR images following the Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) guidelines.

PI-RADS v2.0
Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) version 2.0. [PI-RADS].

PI-RADS v2.1
Prostate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) version 2.1 [PI-RADS v2.1].

Diffusion-weighted Acquisition Highest b-value image
Image from a diffusion-weighted acquisition corresponding to the highest b-value.

Dynamic Contrast-Enhanced Acquisition
Image acquisition that involves injection of a contrast agent into the bloodstream.

Dynamic Contrast-Enhanced Acquisition Subtraction image
Image obtained as a difference in image intensities between two phases of a dynamic contrast-enhanced acquisition.

Utricle cyst
Area of focal dilatation that occurs within the prostatic utricle.

Protocol not followed
Imaging protocol was not followed.

Coil placement concern
Based on image appearance, the coil was not placed correctly.

Coil selection concern
Incorrect coil was selected during MR acquisition.

concept.display: Study performed did not match request
concept.definition:
Study performed did not match request
The imaging procedure performed did not correspond to what was requested.

Incomplete study
Study is missing data.

Suboptimal patient preparation
Some patient preparation procedures were not performed sufficiently with respect to what was expected.

Anatomy coverage incomplete
Coverage of the imaged anatomy is not complete.

Poor FOV selection
Choice of Field of View size or position is not fit for the purpose of the acquisition.

Poor SNR
Signal-to-noise characteristics are insufficient for the purpose of the acquisition.

Poor contrast timing
Timing of the contrast injection relative to the timing of the image acquisition was not properly selected.

Inadequate contrast enhancement
Contrast enhancement observed in the image is not sufficient for the purpose of the acquisition.

Subtraction image missing
The study lacks a sufficient set of subtraction images.

Unwanted subtraction images
Extra subtraction image sets are present that are incorrect or confusing.

Expected b-value is missing
Diffusion-weighted MR image obtained with an expected b-value is not present.

concept.display: Severe distortion in the area of interest
concept.definition:
Severe distortion in the area of interest
Severe geometric distortions are present in the image, and are affecting the area of interest in the image.

Expected ADC map is missing
Apparent Diffusion parametric map image is missing, but was expected.

concept.display: Distortion artifact in the area of interest
concept.definition:
Distortion artifact in the area of interest
Geometric distortions are present in the image, and are affecting the area of interest in the image.

concept.display: No family history of prostate cancer
concept.definition:
No family history of prostate cancer
There is no history of prostate cancer in the patients family.

Pre-biopsy localization of prostate lesion
The purpose of imaging is to identify and localize targets suspicious of the presence of prostate cancer prior to biopsy.

Active surveillance of prostate cancer
Continual monitoring of a patient with localized prostate cancer, with a view to curative intent, according to locally agreed pathways. After [Kuru 2013]

Assess change
The need to detect or measure the amount of change in the condition.

Focal abnormality
Abnormality localized at a focus, central point or locus. [PI-RADS]

Non-focal abnormality
Abnormality not localized to a single focus. [PI-RADS]

Partially encapsulated
Partially but not entirely surrounded (bounded) by a distinct tissue layer, such as a smooth low-signal line on MRI. [PI-RADS]

Completely encapsulated
Entirely surrounded (bounded) by a distinct tissue layer, such as a smooth low-signal line on MRI, in more than one spatial dimension (at least two imaging planes). [PI-RADS]

ADC Hyperintense
Having higher signal intensity (more intense, brighter) than background tissue on the apparent diffusion coefficient map. [PI-RADS]

ADC Hypointense
Having lower intensity (darker) than a reference background tissue on apparent diffusion coefficient map.

Persistent delayed phase: Type 1 curve
Continued increase of signal intensity over time. [PI-RADS]

Plateau delayed phase: Type 2 curve
Signal intensity does not change over time after its initial rise, flat; plateau refers to signal that varies <10% from the peak signal over the duration of the DCE MRI. [PI-RADS]

Washout delayed phase: Type 3 curve
Signal intensity decreases after its highest point after its initial rise. [PI-RADS]

Positive DCE
Focal, early enhancement corresponding to a focal peripheral zone of transition zone lesion on T2 and/or DWI MRI. [PI-RADS]

Negative DCE
Lack of early enhancement. Diffuse enhancement not corresponding to a focal lesion on T2 and/or DWI MRI. Focal enhancement corresponding to a BPH lesion. [PI-RADS]

Early Contrast Enhancement
Contrast-enhanced is observed in the early stage following contrast injection

Diffuse Contrast Enhancement
Contrast enhancement is non-focal and diffused over a region.

Focal Contrast Enhancement
Contrast enhancement is concentrated in a focal tissue area.

Perfluorocarbon
Class of organofluorine compounds containing only carbon and fluorine.

ESUR 2012 prostate MRI acquisition requirements
Prostate MRI technical acquisition requirements defined in [ESUR Guidelines].

PI-RADS 2.0 prostate MRI acquisition requirements
Prostate MRI technical acquisition requirements defined in PI-RADS 2.0 [PI-RADS].

PI-RADS 2.1 prostate MRI acquisition requirements
Prostate MRI technical acquisition requirements defined in PI-RADS 2.1 [PI-RADS v2.1].

2D Shear Wave Elastography
A high-speed ultrasound imaging technique that quantitatively assesses the stiffness/elasticity of tissue based on the tracking of the propagation of a shear-wave and measuring its velocity over a 2D area.

3D Shear Wave Elastography
A high-speed ultrasound imaging technique that quantitatively assesses the stiffness/elasticity of tissue based on the tracking of the propagation of a shear-wave and measuring its velocity over a 3D volume.

Shear Wave Speed
The velocity at which a shear-wave propagates through a substance or tissue.  The shear wave speed (SWS) is correlated with the elasticity of the substance or tissue.

Shear Wave Dispersion Slope
The rate at which shear wave speed is attenuated with changes in the frequency of the shear wave. The dispersion slope is correlated with both the elasticity and the viscosity of the substance or tissue.

ROI Depth
Distance from the ultrasound probe surface to the geometric center of the ROI.

Interquartile Range of population
The width of the center range within which 50% of the measured values in a reference population fall. The IQR may also be described as the first quartile value subtracted from the third quartile value, or equivalently the 25th percentile value subtracted from the 75th percentile value.

concept.display: Interquartile Range to Median Ratio of population
concept.definition:
Interquartile Range to Median Ratio of population
The interquartile range value of a population divided by the median value of the same population. IQR/M, which is one way to describe the variability of a set of measurements, is sometimes used as a metric of measurement quality.

Point Shear Wave Elastography
A high-speed ultrasound imaging technique that quantitatively assesses the stiffness/elasticity of tissue based on the tracking of the propagation of a shear-wave and measuring its velocity at a point.

left ventricle apical anteroseptal segment
A segment of wall of the left ventricle at the apical level whose circumferential extent aligns with that of the anteroseptal segments at the mid and basal levels.
Defined in [Voigt 2015].

left ventricle apical inferoseptal segment
A segment of wall of the left ventricle at the apical level whose circumferential extent aligns with that of the inferoseptal segments at the mid and basal levels.
Defined in [Voigt 2015].

left ventricle apical inferolateral segment
A segment of wall of the left ventricle at the apical level whose circumferential extent aligns with that of the inferolateral segments at the mid and basal levels.
Defined in [Voigt 2015].

left ventricle apical anterolateral segment
A segment of wall of the left ventricle at the apical level whose circumferential extent aligns with that of the anterolateral segments at the mid and basal levels.
Defined in [Voigt 2015].

Isocentric Setup Method
Method to position the patient such that the device isocenter is at a specific location in the patient. For a radiotherapeutic treatment, this allows rotational delivery of radiation treatment fields that maintain a focus on that location.

Controlled SSD Setup Method
Method to position the patient such that the distance between the radiation source and the patient skin is a specific value.

TBI Setup Method
Method to position the patient at an extended distance from the radiation source, typically 2-6 meters, to create a large treatment field for total body irradiation (TBI).

Stereotactic Setup Method
Method to position the patient using high-accuracy localization imaging from multiple angles. Typically combined with rigorous fixation to reduce patient motion.

Skin Apposition Setup Method
Method to position the patient using three-dimensional skin surface registration.

Ocular Gaze Setup Method
Method to set up the patient for ocular treatments by focusing the patients gaze on a particular location.

Patient Shielding Procedure
Preparation procedure to set up devices to shield parts of the patient from radiation.

Patient Fixation Procedure
Preparation procedure to set up devices to fixate parts of the patient. Fixation involves both preventing motion of the patient part and putting the patient part into an intended configuration.

Patient Alignment Procedure
Preparation procedure to orient and position parts of the patient with respect to a physical reference.

Patient Motion Management Setup Procedure
Preparation procedure for controlling or compensating for motion of parts of the patient.

Cavity radiation shield
Device to protect anatomical structures within a body cavity.

Independent radiation shield
A radiation shielding device that is not in contact with the patient or the treatment delivery device.

Optical Distance Meter
An optical distance measuring device.

Mechanical Pointer
A mechanical distance measuring device.

Radiofrequency Transponder
Radiofrequency-based positioning beacon that responds to interrogation.

Infrared Marker
A device that reflects infrared light. Often used to position patients.

Radioactive Marker
A device that emits radiation from a radioactive source. Often used to position patients.

Thermal Imager
A device that produces a temperature map.

Combined Structured Light/Thermal Imager
A device that projects a controlled pattern of light and captures data based on infrared and visible light measurements.

Ocular Fixation Light
A light to which the patients gaze is aligned.

Coaching Device
Device to help patients to follow certain instructions.

Patient Distraction Device
Device to hold the attention of the patient. May be used to reduce the anxiety or discomfort of the patient during a procedure.

Collision checks
Procedure to minimize risk of collision between a primary device, the patient, and associated devices.

Breast Bridge
Device used to position the breast.

Abdominal Compression Belt
Belt used to limit abdominal motion by compressing the abdomen.

Abdominal Compression Arch
Arch-shaped device used to limit abdominal motion by maintaining pressure on the abdomen.

Head Fixation Board
A board to which the patients head is fixed to prevent the patient from moving relative to the tabletop. Typically the patients head is fixed with a mask.

Couch Index Label
A label designating a specific location on an patient support table top.

Fixation Device Angle
Positioning angle on a fixation device with a single degree of angular freedom.

Abdominal Compression Plate Position Number
The number indicating the position of the plate of an abdominal compression device.

Abdominal Compression Belt Length
Length of the part of the abdominal compression belt being used to compress the abdomen.

Abdominal Compression Belt Pressure
Pressure applied to the abdomen by the abdominal compression belt.

Referenced Patient Alignment Reference
References to SOP Instances providing the basis for patient alignment. May contain the intended orientation. The basis for alignment is also referred to as the alignment reference.

RT Radiation previously delivered
The RT Radiation has been already delivered in a previous Treatment Session.

Treatment unnecessary
It has been assessed that the delivery of the Treatment is unnecessary to meet the current treatment goals.

Treatment exceeds patient tolerance
It has been assessed that the delivery of the Treatment would result in effects that exceed the physical or psychological tolerance of the patient.

Radiotherapy Fiducial
Fiducial defined or used during a radiotherapeutic procedure, e.g., treatment planning or positioning.

Longitudinal Lagrangian Strain
Lagrangian strain parallel to the reference contour (i.e. in the longitudinal direction) calculated as: SL(t)=(L(t) -L0)/L0, where L(t) is the length at a given point t in time and L0 is the reference length at the reference time t0.
Strain values are negative with shortening. Due to the common convention of using end-diastole as the t0 reference time, echocardiography strain values are typically negative.
Natural strain differs from Lagrangian strain by using t-1 as the reference time for each time t rather than t0. JASE recommends using Lagrangian strain, noting Natural strain can be computed if needed.
Definitions for a common standard for 2D speckle tracking echocardiography: consensus document of the EACVI/ASE/Industry Task Force to standardize deformation imaging, Eur Heart J Cardiovasc Imaging.2015 Jan;16(1):1-11 and JASE 2015 Feb;28(2):183-93.

Peak Longitudinal Lagrangian Strain
Peak value of longitudinal Lagrangian strain during an identified interval, such as systole or a full cardiac cycle.

concept.display: Time to Peak Longitudinal Lagrangian Strain
concept.definition:
Time to Peak Longitudinal Lagrangian Strain
The time from the beginning of the interval to the time of the peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain.

Mechanical Dispersion
The standard deviation of the time to peak longitudinal strain value for different myocardial segments. Typically assessed over 18-segments of the left ventricle.
Haugaa, K., et al, "Mechanical Dispersion Assessed by Myocardial Strain in Patients After Myocardial Infarction for Risk Prediction of Ventricular Arrhythmia" J Am Coll Cardiol Cardiovasc Imaging. 2010 Mar, 3 (3) 247256.

Longitudinal Lagrangian Strain Rate
Rate of change of longitudinal strain over time.

Radial Lagrangian Strain
Lagrangian strain in the wall of a cavity perpendicular to the longitudinal strain and towards the center of the cavity.

Radial Lagrangian Strain Rate
Rate of change of radial Lagrangian strain over time.

Circumferential Lagrangian Strain
Lagrangian strain tangential to the reference contour, perpendicular to the longitudinal strain, with positive values in the counterclockwise direction when viewed from the apex.

Circumferential Lagrangian Strain Rate
Rate of change of circumferential Lagrangian strain over time.

2D Speckle Tracking
A method of analyzing the motion of tissue, such as the heart muscle or blood, by using naturally occurring speckle patterns in 2D ultrasound imaging.

3D Speckle Tracking
A method of analyzing the motion of tissue, such as the heart muscle or blood, by using naturally occurring speckle patterns in 3D ultrasound imaging.

Apical four chamber RV Focused
A view obtained from the apical four chamber view by angling the beam medially toward the patients right shoulder to better include the right ventricle.
Recommended in "Standardization of left atrial, right ventricular, and right atrial deformation imaging using two dimensional speckle tracking echocardiography: a consensus document of the EACVI/ASE/Industry Task Force to standardize deformation imaging " European Heart Journal  Cardiovascular Imaging (2018) 19, 591600.

Apical four chamber RV Modified
A view obtained from the apical four chamber view by angling the beam laterally toward the patients left shoulder to better include the right ventricle.
Alternative to RV focused per "Recommendations for Cardiac Chamber Quantification by Echocardiography in Adults: An Update from the American Society of Echocardiography and the European Association of Cardiovascular Imaging" J Am Soc Echocardiogr 2015;28:1-39.

Endocardial Method
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated endocardial boundary.

Epicardial Method
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated epicardial boundary.

Myocardial Midlayer Method
A measurement method that uses a contour representing the estimated mid-layer of the myocardium (between the endocardium and epicardium).

LV End-systolic GLS Multiview Mean (Endocardial)
The longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV End-systolic Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LV End-systolic GLS 4CH (Endocardial)
The longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical four chamber view at end systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.
Sometimes abbreviated GLS4C.

LV End-systolic GLS 2CH (Endocardial)
The longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical two chamber view at end systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.
Sometimes abbreviated GLS2C.

LV End-systolic GLS ALAX (Endocardial)
The longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical long axis view at end systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.
Sometimes abbreviated GLSALAX.

concept.display: LV Peak Systolic GLS Multiview Mean (Endocardial)
concept.definition:
LV Peak Systolic GLS Multiview Mean (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV Peak Systolic Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LV Peak Systolic GLS 4CH (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical four chamber view during systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV Peak Systolic GLS 2CH (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical two chamber view during systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV Peak Systolic GLS ALAX (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical long axis view during systole using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV Peak GLS Multiview Mean (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle calculated as the arithmetic mean of LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain 4CH (Endocardial), LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain 2CH (Endocardial), and LV Peak Global Longitudinal Strain ALAX (Endocardial).

LV Peak GLS 4CH (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical four chamber view over the cardiac cycle using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV Peak GLS 2CH (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical two chamber view over the cardiac cycle using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV Peak GLS ALAX (Endocardial)
The peak longitudinal Lagrangian strain of the left ventricle measured along the entire myocardial length in 2D Speckle mode in the apical long axis view over the cardiac cycle using the endocardial method.
The measurement may have been taken at any point in the respiration cycle.

LV End-systolic Mechanical Dispersion
The mechanical dispersion of the left ventricle in 2D Speckle mode at end systole.
The measurement may have been taken using any view, using any segment model (16, 17 or 18-segment) and at any point in the respiration cycle.

Mitral Valve Closure
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the mitral valve nominally finishes closing.

Mitral Valve Opening
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the mitral valve nominally begins opening.

Aortic Valve Closure
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the aortic valve nominally finishes closing.

Aortic Valve Opening
The point in time in a cardiac cycle when the aortic valve nominally begins opening.

Fp9
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior frontopolar, left.
[Seeck 2017].

Fp10
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior frontopolar, right.
[Seeck 2017].

AF9
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior anterior frontal, left.
[Seeck 2017].

AF10
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior anterior frontal, right.
[Seeck 2017].

PO9
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior parietooccipital, left.
[Seeck 2017].

PO10
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior parietooccipital, right.
[Seeck 2017].

O9
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior occipital, left.
[Seeck 2017].

O10
EEG electrode placement on the head located inferior occipital, right.
[Seeck 2017].
Coronary Artery Disease Assessment
oronary Artery Disease Assessment Modifier

concept.display: Coronary Artery Disease Stenosis Assessment Modifier
concept.definition: Coronary Artery Disease Stenosis Assessment Modifier

0 - Documented absence of CAD
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 0%.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

1 - Minimal non-obstructive CAD
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 1-24%.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

2 - Mild non-obstructive CAD
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 25-49%.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

3 - Moderate stenosis
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 50-69%.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

4 - Severe stenosis
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 70-99%, or left main coronary stenosis is >50%, or coronary stenosis is >=70% in 3 vessels.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

4A - Severe stenosis
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 70-99% stenosis.
CAD-RADS assessment sub-category [CAD-RADS].

4B - Severe stenosis
Left main coronary stenosis is >50% or coronary stenosis is >=70% in 3 vessels.
CAD-RADS assessment sub-category [CAD-RADS].

5 - Total coronary occlusion
Degree of maximal coronary stenosis is 100% (total occlusion).
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

N - Non-diagnostic study
No more than mild coronary stenosis in interpretable segments, and one or more vessel segments non-diagnostic.
CAD-RADS assessment category [CAD-RADS].

N - Non-diagnostic segments
One or more vessel segments were non-diagnostic for coronary stenosis.
CAD-RADS assessment category modifier [CAD-RADS].

S - Stent
At least one coronary stent is present in the coronary system.
CAD-RADS assessment category modifier [CAD-RADS].

G - Graft
At least one coronary artery bypass graft is present.
CAD-RADS assessment category modifier [CAD-RADS].

V - Vulnerable plaque
Vulnerable plaque or high risk plaque features are present.
CAD-RADS assessment category modifier [CAD-RADS].

Titanium alloy (Titanium Molybdenum-15 Zirconium-5 Aluminium-3)
Wrought titanium 15-molybdenum 5-zirconium 3-aluminium alloy.

RT Segment Material
Material identifiers used during or for an RT planning process.

Dose Limit Interlock
An interlock triggered by reaching a predefined dose limit.

Clearance Interlock
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between objects.

Machine Clearance Interlock
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between machine and machine.

Patient Clearance Interlock
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between machine and patient.

Accessory Clearance Interlock
An interlock triggered by the occurrence, or anticipation, of a physical collision caused by lack of separation distance between an accessory and the machine, patient or another accessory.
An accessory can be e.g., an electron applicator or a stereotactic cone.

Out of Tolerance Interlock
An interlock triggered by an actual value being outside of tolerance from the planned value.

Interlock Resolved
The interlock was resolved, and treatment delivery was continued.

CT Dose Length Product Sub-Total
The total dose length product for irradiation events within in the defined scope of accumulation that were computed using the same phantom.
E.g., when head and body are imaged within the same study and 16cm and 32cm phantoms are used, respectively.

RT Registration Mark
Marker used in a registration process.

Isodose Volume
A volume whose surface represents an isodose.

Radiotherapy Dose Region
Region defined by the spatial extent of a radiation dose.

Quality control material image
Images that contain quality control material for the current procedure.

Tissue not of interest
Tissue that is other than that which is of interest for the purpose of the task.
E.g., segmented non-brain tissue in an image where the primary purpose is to segment the brain and/or its structure, and non-brain tissue that is distinct from background needs to be identified.

Data Not Accessible from Storage
Requested data cannot be read from storage media, e.g., data physically deleted, or storage media no longer available.

Processed Key Object Selection
The SOP Instance is a Key Object Selection Document, used for referenced object change management, that has had its directives processed and is no longer to be used (see [IHE RAD TF-1].

Replaced by Alternate Representation
The SOP Instance has been replaced by a SOP Instance with an alternate encoding. The alternate encoding may utilize a different SOP Class or have different image quality characteristics (e.g., lossy compression).

Reference Measurement Group
A grouping of related measurements and calculations that share a common context and that serves as a reference against which similar measurement groups are compared.

Particle Displacement Method
A method for detecting a shear wave in ultrasound data based on the displacement of particles relative to their referenced baseline positions.

Particle Velocity Method
A method for detecting a shear wave in ultrasound data based on estimated particle velocity. Particle velocity is estimated from frame to frame particle displacement.

concept.display: Shear Wave Dispersion Slope Center Frequency
concept.definition:
Shear Wave Dispersion Slope Center Frequency
The center frequency of the range over which the shear wave dispersion slope was assessed.

Shear Wave Detection Method
Method used to detect and characterize a shear wave motion signal in an ultrasound signal.

Butterworth filter
A signal processing filter of the Butterworth type.

Chebyshev filter
A signal processing filter of the Chebyshev type.

Elliptic filter
An elliptic signal processing filter.

Bessel filter
A signal processing filter of the Bessel type.

Gaussian filter
A signal processing filter of the Gaussian type

K-type filter
A K-type (constant k) signal processing filter.

M-derived filter
An M-derived (m-type) signal processing filter.

Double-m-derived filter
A double-m-derived (mm'-type) signal processing filter.

Bode filter
A signal processing filter of the Bode type.

Zobel filter
A signal processing filter of the Zobel type.

FIR filter
A finite impulse response (FIR) signal processing filter.

CIC filter
A cascaded integratorcomb (CIC) signal processing filter.

IIR filter
An infinite impulse response (IIR) signal processing filter.

Biquad filter
A biquadratic signal processing filter (second order recursive linear filter).

Hz normalized
Frequency in Hz divided by  of the sampling rate.

Hz angular
Frequency in Hz divided by  of the sampling rate and then multiplied by  (pi).

Magnitude normalized
Ratio of output magnitude to input magnitude, has no units and a value between 0-1.

Specific observation subject class
The type of entity that is the subject of a specific observation, such as a measurement or qualitative evaluation. E.g., a region of interest, image, series of images, study or patient.
Note
This is distinct from the Subject Class used in Observation Context, which more generally specifies the entire subject, usually the patient.

Image frame
A single two-dimensional pixel plane of an image.
Note
Usually used in the context of a multi-frame image.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Integrated Dose MV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Integrated Dose MV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using continuous megavoltage acquisition during treatment delivery.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette MV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette MV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using a radiation-sensitive film suited for megavoltage radiation.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette kV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Film Cassette kV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using a radiation-sensitive film suited for photon radiation.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT kV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT kV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using kilovoltage Cone-Beam CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT kV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT kV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using kilovoltage conventional CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT MV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Cone-Beam CT MV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using megavoltage Cone-Beam CT imaging.

concept.display: RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT MV
concept.definition:
RT Patient Position Acquisition, Conventional CT MV
Acquisition of patient positioning information using megavoltage conventional CT imaging.

Nominal Imaging Source Location
The point location defined as the nominal source of radiation used for imaging.

RT Patient Positioning Reference Image
Image(s) of the patient used to provide a reference for positioning of the patient for the planned treatment.

Acquisition Initiation Type
The type of method used to start the acquisition.

Acquisition Initiation not defined
The acquisition trigger is not specified. Acquisition may be initiated manually by the device operator.

concept.display: Acquisition Initiation before start of Radiation
concept.definition:
Acquisition Initiation before start of Radiation
The acquisition is started before delivering the therapeutic radiation. It is expected that the therapeutic beam is not started before the acquisition is completed.

concept.display: Acquisition Initiation after end of Radiation
concept.definition:
Acquisition Initiation after end of Radiation
The acquisition is started after delivering the therapeutic radiation.

Acquisition Initiation by triggering parameter
The acquisition is started when the triggering parameter reaches specific value(s).

Incremental Acquisition Triggering
Flag denoting whether the acquisition is to be repeated in regular intervals separated by a certain increment.

Meterset
A single parameter from which the absorbed dose delivered can be calculated through a calibration procedure with additional information.

Source Continuous Roll Angle
Angle in degrees about the Y-axis of the Equipment Coordinate System by which the source is rotated. A Continuous Rotation Angle is an angle in the range (-,+). Continuous Rotation Angle represent a rotation direction and magnitude. The magnitude is not limited to be between 0 and 360 degrees.

Time after start of Radiation
Time elapsed after the start of the delivery of an RT Radiation.

concept.display: Percentage of expected beam-on time of Radiation
concept.definition:
Percentage of expected beam-on time of Radiation
Delivered percentage of the duration of a Radiation at a given point in time. The denominator is the duration of time that the beam is expected to be on between the start and the end of the delivery of an RT Radiation. The numerator is the duration of time that the beam has been on since the start of the first beam-on. Both durations exclude 'beam-hold' periods within the treatment delivery (e.g. during gated treatments).

concept.display: IEC61217 Imaging Source to Axis Distance
concept.definition:
IEC61217 Imaging Source to Axis Distance
Distance from the imaging source, in mm, to the gantry rotation axis of a IEC C-Arm Device. This parameter is not specifically defined by [IEC 61217], but is consistent with [IEC 61217]

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Radial Displacement from Isocenter
concept.definition:
IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Radial Displacement from Isocenter
X-Ray Image Receptor Radial Displacement From Isocenter, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by [IEC 61217].

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Longitudinal Displacement
concept.definition:
IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Longitudinal Displacement
X-Ray Image Receptor Longitudinal Displacement, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by [IEC 61217].

concept.display: IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Lateral Displacement
concept.definition:
IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Lateral Displacement
X-Ray Image Receptor Lateral Displacement, in mm (in the IEC GANTRY Coordinate System) as defined by [IEC 61217].

IEC61217 X-Ray Image Receptor Rotation
X-Ray Image Receptor rotation (around the z-axis of the IEC X-RAY IMAGE RECEPTOR Coordinate System) as defined by [IEC 61217]. DICOM represents this value as a Continous Rotation Angle in degrees.

Configured Lowest Imaging Energy
Lowest energy for acquiring an image as configured on the device.

Configured Default Imaging Energy
Default energy for acquiring an image as configured on the device.

Planar matrix ultrasound transducer geometry
Ultrasonic transducer geometry characterized by multiple transducer elements arranged in a grid on a plane.

Hemispherical ultrasound transducer geometry
Ultrasonic transducer geometry characterized by multiple transducer elements arranged on a hemispherical surface.

Single-side illumination
The subject is illuminated from a single direction.

Dual-side illumination
The subject is illuminated from two distinct directions.

Multi-side illumination
The subject is illuminated from more than two (potentially a very large number of) distinct directions.

Through-transducer illumination
The subject is illuminated  through the transducer. Light may pass through the transducer at one or more locations.

Interstitial illumination
The subject is illuminated internally. Light is delivered via a device (other than the transducer) inside the body.

Piezocomposite Transducer
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes Piezo-composite crystalline structures.

MEMS-based Transducer
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes Micro-electro-mechanical systems (MEMS)-based structures.

Interferometric Transducer
Ultrasound Transducer that utilizes interferometric detection systems.

Uniform Speed of Sound Correction
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on a single speed of sound, where the speed for the acoustic coupling medium (if present) is assumed to be the same as for the imaged object.

Dual Speed of Sound Correction
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on two speeds of sound, one for the acoustic coupling medium and one for the imaged object.

Speed of Sound Map Correction
Mechanism for correction of data using a sound propagation model based on a speed of sound map that defines the speed of sound on a per-pixel basis.

Spherical Back Projection
A family of algorithms for reconstructing an image from measured data by back-projection over spheres or parts of spheres. May include linear or nonlinear processing steps before and/or after the back-projection step. Includes methods termed beamforming and delay-and-sum.

Numerical Acoustic Model
A family of algorithms for reconstructing an image from measured data by iteratively adjusting the image to minimize a cost function between the data and a numerical model or that uses non-iterative (e.g. time-reversal) methods, or that performs inversion of a forward model matrix.

Blood Deoxygenation Level
Signal intensity of a Blood Deoxygenation Level image.

Scan Spot Interlock
An interlock triggered during scan spot delivery that is not covered by a more specific code.

Scan Spot Position Interlock
An interlock triggered by the scan spot position being outside of tolerance.

Scan Spot Size Interlock
An interlock triggered by the scan spot size being outside of tolerance.

Scan Spot Meterset Interlock
An interlock triggered by the Meterset delivered for a spot being outside of tolerance.

concept.display: Radiation Detected During Beam Hold Interlock
concept.definition:
Radiation Detected During Beam Hold Interlock
An interlock triggered by detection of radiation when the beam is supposed to be off.

MLC Position Interlock
An interlock triggered by a multileaf collimator (MLC) leaf position being outside of tolerance.

Meterset Rate Interlock
An interlock triggered by the detected Meterset rate being outside of tolerance.

Beam Energy Interlock
An interlock triggered by the detected energy of the beam being outside of tolerance.

Skin lesion color
A visual assessment of the coloration of a skin lesion.

Pre-surgical anatomy
The anatomy of the subject prior to the effect of a surgical procedure.

Sleep Stage N1
Non-REM Sleep Stage 1 is the transition between wakefulness and sleep.
[Berry 2012]

Sleep Stage N2
Non-REM Sleep Stage 2 is light sleep.
[Berry 2012]

Sleep Stage N3
Non-REM Sleep Stage 3 is deep sleep.
[Berry 2012]

Seat Pan Height
The adjustable distance between the seat pan (the resting place for the patients bottom) and the nominal floor of the upright fixation device. Adjustment allows the feet to be placed firmly on the nominal floor without the legs being stretched or too cramped.

Seat Pan Pitch Angle
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the seat pan. Adjustment provides thigh support while pitching downward changes the angle between the upper legs (knee to hip) and the abdomen.  An angle of zero is a typical sitting position. A large positive angle, such as 75, puts a person in a nearly standing stance.

Backrest Pitch Angle
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the backrest. Adjustment controls the angle of the patients back (when in a nominally seated or upright position) with respect to gravity. Typically tilted back a bit so that the back is resting and slightly supported. An angle of zero means the backrest is vertical. A positive angle means the patient is reclining.

Shin Rest Position
The adjustable distance between the shin rest and the nominal center under the seat of the chair. Adjustment accommodates the leg length and stance of the patient (the stance of the patient is adjusted primarily through the seat pan pitch angle and the backrest fixation pitch angle).

Heel Stop Position
The adjustable distance between the heel stop and the shin rest. Adjustment accommodates the patient foot size, shin rest position, lower leg length, and the angle of the lower legs with respect to gravity. The zero point is device-specific.

Left Arm Rest Position
The adjustable lateral distance between the left arm rest and patients thorax. The zero point is device-specific.

Left Arm Rest Pitch Angle
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the left arm rest. Adjustment controls one of the angles of the elbow. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

Left Arm Rest Roll Angle
The adjustable angle of the roll of the left arm rest. Adjustment controls the roll angle of the lower arm. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

Right Arm Rest Position
The adjustable lateral distance between the right arm rest and the patients thorax. The zero point is device-specific.

Right Arm Rest Pitch Angle
The adjustable angle of the pitch of the right arm rest. Adjustment controls one of the angles of the elbow. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

Right Arm Rest Roll Angle
The adjustable angle of the roll of the right arm rest. Adjustment controls the roll angle of the lower arm. An angle of zero means the arm rest is parallel to the ground.

Hand Grips Presence
Whether the hand grips are inserted into the backrest or not. If hand grips are present, it is implicit that the patient is intended to grip the hand grips with their hands.

Shin Rest
A fixation device that immobilizes the patients shins by the natural weight and pressure of the shins against the device.

Heel Stop
A fixation device that immobilizes the heels of the patient in counterpoint to the shin rest.

Hand Grips
A fixation device placed above the patients shoulders along the back rest, such that when gripped, ensures that the patients arms and elbows are lifted and not obstructing lateral access to the chest or breasts.

Seat Pan
A fixation device that supports the thighs (and bottom) of the patient. The seat pan is distinct from the backrest.

Pattern Event
Classification of a Waveform annotation as a pattern.

EEG Annotation
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to EEG.

EMG Annotation
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to ECG.

EOG Annotation
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to EOG.

Device-related and Environment-related Event
Classification of a Waveform annotation as an event, which occurred in the recording device or in the environment (e.g. the room).

Patient Consciousness
Classification of a Waveform annotation as a description of the patients consciousness.

ECG Annotation
Classification of a Waveform annotation as belonging to ECG.

Neurophysiology Recording Annotations
A Waveform annotation report comprising neurophysiology annotations added during recording.

Neurophysiology Post-hoc Review Annotations
A Waveform annotation report containing neurophysiology annotations resulting from post-hoc review.

Neurophysiology Automated Analysis Annotations
A Waveform annotation report containing neurophysiology annotations resulting from automated analysis.

Waveform Annotations
A container that groups waveform annotations.

Procedure annotated
The neurophysiology or cardiology procedure to which annotations apply.

Waveform Annotation Group
A container that groups a set of associated waveform annotations.

Waveform Annotation Group Number
A number identifying a set of associated annotations.

Waveform Annotation Group Label
A text describing a set of associated annotations.

Waveform Annotation Modifier
Coded modifier for a coded waveform annotation.

Annotation Note
A free text information.

Waveform Library
A container that references properties of involved waveforms

Waveform Library Group
A container that groups common information about a set of involved waveforms

concept.display: Waveform Library Entry Multiplex Group Descriptors
concept.definition:
Waveform Library Entry Multiplex Group Descriptors
A container that groups common information about a waveform multiplex group comprising a set of recording channel

Multiplex Group Number
Identifying number of a waveform multiplex group

Multiplex Group UID
Unique identifier of a waveform multiplex group

Sampling Frequency
Frequency of waveform digitalization

Number of Channels
Number of channels in a waveform multiplex group

Acquisition DateTime
Date and Time of an Acquisition

Synchronization Frame of Reference UID
UID of common synchronization environment.

Line noise artifact
50 Hz or 60 Hz line noise artifact from a power supply

Video recording on
Video recording turned on automatically or by the operator

Video recording off
Video recording turned off automatically or by the operator

Preamplifier connected
Machine code for when the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) is connected to the recording device.

Preamplifier disconnected
Machine code for when preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) is disconnected.

Breakout box connected
A breakout box was connected or reconnected.
A breakout box is a box into which electrode cables are plugged, but the analog electrical signal of those cables is passed from the breakout box to the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) through another cable, so there is no preamp or A/D conversion in the box.

Breakout box disconnected
A breakout box was disconnected.
A breakout box is a box into which electrode cables are plugged, but the analog electrical signal of those cables is passed from the breakout box to the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings) through another cable, so there is no preamp or A/D conversion in the box.

Event button pressed
The event button was pressed for the purpose of capturing an event.
The event button is a button that a medical staff member, patient, or family/friend of patient can press when the patient (who is getting the recording) has an event (such as an abnormal movement or seizure).

Event button test
The event button was pressed for the purpose of testing.
Testing the event button usually occurs at the beginning of a neurophysiology recording to make sure the mechanism is working.

Tap test begin
A tap test has started.
A tap test is when the operator taps each electrode in sequence to verify that each electrode is plugged into the correct channel of the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings).

Tap test end
A tap test has finished.
A tap test is when the operator taps each electrode in sequence to verify that each electrode is plugged into the correct channel of the preamplifier (the headbox in case of EEG recordings).

Follicle Count Group
The counted group of follicles that fall within a specified type and size range.

Diameter Range Minimum Value
The lowest value that is included in a diameter range.

Diameter Range Maximum Value
The highest value that is included in a diameter range.

Volume Range Minimum Value
The lowest value that is included in a volume range.

Volume Range Maximum Value
The highest value that is included in a volume range.

Number of Follicles in Range
The number of follicles observed in a specified size range.

Total Antral Follicle Count
The total number of antral follicles counted in both ovaries.

Follicle Type
The type of ovarian follicle as determined by its developmental stage.

Dominant Follicle
An antral follicle that has grown to dominate its neighboring follicles which then undergo atresia.
                         Typically, only one or two antral follicles will become dominant in each cycle and mature to ovulation.
See also Terms and Definitions in Coelo Neto et al, 2017. Counting ovarian antral follicles by ultrasound: a practical guide. Available at: http://obgyn.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/uog.18945.

Antral Follicle
An ovarian follicle that has progressed from the secondary stage and has developed a small fluid-filled cavity called the antrum.
                         Antral Follicles are also referred to as Tertiary Follicles or Graafian Follicles.

Secondary Follicle
An ovarian follicle that has progressed from the primary stage and has added theca cells.

Primary Follicle
An ovarian follicle that has been activated from the primordial stage.

Primordial Follicle
An ovarian follicle that is quiescent in its original state.

Follicle Count Group Identifier
The identifier of a referenced follicle count group.

Dice Similarity Coefficient
A measure of the pair-wise overlap of two sets defined as two times the intersection of the two samples, divided by the sum of the two samples. Also known as the SrensenDice coefficient. The samples may be points representing pixels or voxels in a geometric region.
1. Dice LR. Measures of the Amount of Ecologic Association Between Species. Ecol. 1945 Jul;26(3):297302. doi:10.2307/1932409
2. Taha AA, Hanbury A. Metrics for evaluating 3D medical image segmentation: analysis, selection, and tool. BMC Med Imag. 2015 Dec;15(1):29. doi:10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x

Jaccard Index
A measure of the pair-wise overlap of two samples defined as the intersection of the two regions, divided by the union of the two samples. Also known as the Intersection Over Union (IoU). The samples may be points representing pixels or voxels in a geometric region.
1. Jaccard P. The Distribution of the Flora of the Alpine Zone. New Phytol. 1912 Feb;11(2):3750. doi:10.1111/j.1469-8137.1912.tb05611.x
2. Taha AA, Hanbury A. Metrics for evaluating 3D medical image segmentation: analysis, selection, and tool. BMC Med Imag. 2015 Dec;15(1):29. doi:10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x

Number of pixels
A count of the number of pixels in an image or a region of an image.

Number of voxels
A count of the number of voxels in a volume.

Mean intensity projection
Values are derived by mean intensity projection of acquired data.

Median intensity projection
Values are derived by median intensity projection of acquired data

Summation projection
Values are derived by summation of values in the projection of acquired data

Ventriculoatrial time interval
Ventriculoatrial time interval (VA time), defined as the interval between the onset of ventricular systole and the onset of atrial systole.
Recommended for assessment of Fetal arrhythmia per Fetal Echo Guideline Japan  Second edition 2021.
                        Commonly measured by doppler using a view aligned with a pair of locations: the Superior Vena Cava and the Ascending Aorta, or the Left Ventricular Inflow Tract and the Left Ventricular Outflow Tract, or a Pulmonary Artery and Pulmonary Vein.
                        In a coded measurement, when only one finding location is recorded, the partner location is implicit.

Atrioventricular time interval
Atrioventricular time interval (AV time or AVI), defined as the interval between the onset of atrial systole and the onset of ventricular systole.
Commonly measured by doppler using a view aligned with a pair of locations: the Superior Vena Cava (SVC) and the Ascending Aorta, or the Left Ventricular Inflow Tract and the Left Ventricular Outflow Tract, or a Pulmonary Artery and a Pulmonary Vein.
                         In a coded measurement, when only one finding location is recorded, the partner location is implicit.

Left Atrium-Descending Aorta Distance
The shortest distance (LD) between any point on the inside of the atrium wall and any point on the outside of the descending thoracic aorta wall measured in a four-chamber view of the heart.

Post-Left Atrium Space Index
Post-Left Atrium Space (PLAS) Index is the distance between the left atrium and the descending thoracic aorta divided by the diameter of the descending thoracic aorta, where both measurements are taken in the same view (thus defining the point in the descending thoracic aorta for the diameter measurement).
Used in fetal echo for diagnosis of isolated Total Anomalous Pulmonary Venous Connection (TAPVC).
                         doi:10.9794/jspccs.32.387

Cerebroplacental ratio
The pulsatility index at the middle cerebral artery of the fetus divided by the pulsatility index at the umbilical artery.
                         Abbreviated CPR.

Umbilicocerebral ratio
The pulsatility index at the umbilical artery divided by the pulsatility index at the middle cerebral artery of the fetus.

IVC preload index
The ratio of the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave to the peak forward flow during the S-wave, as measured at the inferior vena cava using pulsed-wave doppler.
                         Abbreviated a/S.
doi:10.1159/000263589 (1990)
doi:10.1002/uog.142

IVC S/a
The ratio of the peak forward flow during the S-wave to the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave, as measured at the inferior vena cava using pulsed-wave doppler.
                         This is the inverse of the Preload index.

Peak Velocity Index
A blood flow index calculated by subtracting the peak retrograde flow during the A-wave from the peak forward flow during the S-wave, then dividing by the peak forward flow during the D-wave, i.e., (S-a)/D.
doi:10.1002/uog.902

DV Pulsatility Index in Veins
The pulsatility index measured in the ductus venosus during the full cardiac cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view.
                         Abbreviated PIV.

concept.display: DV Peak Velocity Index in Veins
concept.definition:
DV Peak Velocity Index in Veins
The peak velocity index measured in the ductus venosus during the full cardiac cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view.
                         Abbreviated PVIV.

Right ventricular inlet length
The length of the right ventricle measured at end diastole in 2D mode using a method that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in any view.

Left ventricular inlet length
The length of the left ventricle measured at end diastole in 2D mode using a method that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in any view.

Inlet Included
A method of measuring a cardiac chamber length that includes the inlet portion of the chamber in the length.

Free Cord Loop Method
A  method of measuring hemodynamics in the umbilical cord by taking the measurement in a free loop of the cord.
                         A free loop is a portion of the umbilical cord that is not attached to the fetal body or the placenta and is instead floating freely within the amniotic fluid.

Ductus Arteriosus Arch
The ductal arch formed by the ductus arteriosus as it travels from its origin at the pulmonary artery to the point of entry into the descending aorta.
doi:10.1002/j.2205-0140.2013.tb00243.x

Aortic arch view
A planar view of the heart showing the aortic valve, ascending aorta, aortic arch, descending aorta and inferior vena cava.

concept.display: Oblique short axis view at ductus arteriosus
concept.definition:
Oblique short axis view at ductus arteriosus
A planar oblique short-axis view of the heart showing the pulmonary trunk (main pulmonary artery, right pulmonary artery) and the ductus arteriosus.

concept.display: Short axis view at pulmonary artery level
concept.definition:
Short axis view at pulmonary artery level
A planar short-axis view of the heart showing the pulmonary valve, main pulmonary artery, right and left pulmonary arteries.

Three vessel view
An axial planar view of the heart showing the main pulmonary artery, ascending aorta in cross-section, and superior vena cava (SVC) in cross-section.
                         One or both branch pulmonary arteries may also be included.
                         Abbreviated 3VV.

Three vessel and trachea view
An axial planar view of the heart showing the trachea and the aortic and ductal arches converging to form the proximal descending thoracic aorta.
                         Abbreviated 3VT.

Left ventricular outflow tract view
An axial planar view of the heart showing the subaortic area, aortic valve, supravalvular region, and ascending aorta.

Four chamber view
An axial planar view of the heart showing both ventricles and both atria.
                         The view does not necessarily include the apex of the heart.

Fetal Cardiovascular Profile
Report section for assessment of cardiovascular observations that evaluate fetal well-being.

Hydrops Fetalis Score
A point-based assessment of abnormal fluid accumulation in fetal body areas.
                         This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

Cardiothoracic Size Ratio Score
A point-based assessment of heart size relative to thoracic size based on observations of the circumferences or areas.
                         This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

Cardiac Function Score
A point-based assessment of cardiac function based on observations of valve inflow and regurgitation patterns and ventricular shortening.
                         This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

Venous Doppler Score
A point-based assessment of venous flow based on Doppler observations of the umbilical vein and ductus venosus.
                         This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

Arterial Doppler Score
A point-based assessment of arterial flow based on Doppler observations of the umbilical artery.
                         This is a component of the Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score.

Fetal Cardiovascular Profile Score
A point-based score that sums the scores of five component assessments of cardiovascular observations to evaluate fetal well-being according to
                         Makikallio et al, Human fetal cardiovascular profile score and neonatal outcome in intrauterine growth restriction. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol 2008; 31: 4854
                         doi:10.1002/uog.5210
                         Abbreviated CVPS.

PV VTI Forward
The velocity time integral measured in the pulmonary vein for the antegrade flow during the full cycle in pulsed doppler mode in any view.
                         Forward flow occurs during the D-wave and the S-wave.

PV VTI Reverse
The velocity time integral measured in the pulmonary vein for the retrograde flow during the A-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.

PV VTIR/VTIF ratio
The ratio of the retrograde velocity time integral to the antegrade velocity time integral at the pulmonary vein.

Right Ventricle Cardiac Output
The volume rate of blood output by the right ventricle derived from the right ventricle stroke volume and heart rate.
                         Abbreviated RVCO.

Combined Cardiac Output
The volume rate of blood output by the heart derived from the cardiac output of the left and right ventricles.
                         Abbreviated CCO.

Mitral valve annulus diameter
The diameter of the annulus of the mitral valve measured during diastole in 2D mode in a short axis view at the level of the mitral valve.

Tricuspid valve annulus diameter
The diameter of the annulus of the tricuspid valve measured during diastole in 2D mode in a short axis view at the level of the mitral valve.

IVC S-wave peak velocity
The peak velocity measured in the inferior vena cava during the S-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.

IVC a-wave peak velocity
The peak velocity measured in the inferior vena cava during the a-wave in pulsed doppler mode in any view.
